Goldy Pond

Also known as "Area 08-63", Goldy Pond was originally William Minerva's base for human escapees and located underground to escape detection. It was discovered by the demons and became a secret reserve for hunting humans owned by the demon Lord Bayon. His victims were the children he purchased from the Premium Farms (mainly Grand Valley Orphanage), but sometimes also included humans poached from the outside world. Lambda 7214

"7214", also known as "Lambda 7214" or simply "Lambda", was a research facility where various experiments were conducted on human children from various plantation farms. After being shipped out from Grace Field House, Norman was sent to Lambda where he was experimented on. Norman eventually led a group of kids in an escape from Lambda and destroyed the place in the process.

Ratri Clan

The Ratri Clan (also called the "Ratri family") is a human clan that signed the ancient treaty called "The Promise" 1,000 years ago to separate humans and demons from each other as a way to end a war between the two races. The Ratri Clan oversees the farm system and upholds "The Promise".

Demons

The primary antagonists of the series, the Demons consist of a variety of forms, from mindless monsters with multiple eyes who take the qualities of the animals they devour. Demons who eat humans take on a tall humanoid form resembling humans with Polydactyly and wear armored masks to protect their central eyes, their only truly vital organ. The ruling Demons sponsor the farm system to provide them with a ready source of human flesh, which they require to remain sentient, and sometimes for the pastime of hunting humans.

Trivia

Shirai claims to be not very good at naming characters.[4] This may explain why there are so many unnamed characters in The Promised Neverland series and also why there are a few characters who have the same or very similar names to another character.

The reason most characters have western names as opposed to Japanese names is because Shirai wanted most of the characters to have "universal names" that would be familiar to the most amount of people around the world.
